article.description:
Kevin Bettencourt scored 23 points to help
Bucknell cap a perfect Patriot League season with a 74-59 win over
Holy Cross in the championship game Friday night.
article.headline: Bucknell bests Holy Cross to lock up Patriot League bid
article.linkText: Bucknell nabs NCAA bid, hoping for repeat performance
article.story: LEWISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Bucknell's biggest upset this season would have been missing the NCAA tournament. Put the nation's elite on alert. The Bison are ready to shake up the brackets again and block some top team's path to the Final Four. One year after pulling off a memorable tourney upset, the Bison proved they're no one-season wonder as Kevin Bettencourt scored 23 points to help Bucknell cap a perfect Patriot League season with a 74-59 win over Holy Cross in the championship game Friday night. "I'm not a guy that goes anywhere, but tonight I am," said coach Pat Flannery, wearing a wide smile and championship hat. Bucknell (26-4) went undefeated in Patriot League play, with 14 regular-season wins and three more in the conference tournament to earn its second straight NCAA tournament berth and fourth overall. "I definitely feel relieved," Patriot League player of the year Charles Lee said. "We always say don't let the pressure get to you. But it's hard to not listen to the media, it's all over. I came in very nervous." Well he hid the feeling well, and so did any other Bucknell player who felt the same butterflies. The team from a small private school has been making a habit of beating some of the best known teams in college basketball -- none bigger than a first-round win over third-seeded Kansas in last season's NCAA tournament that catapulted the Bison into the national spotlight. "We haven't snuck up on anybody this year and we still had a pretty successful season," Bettencourt said. Now, they get another chance and it might be hard for a lot of teams to stop Chris McNaughton, Lee and Bettencourt when they're on their game. The trio carried the Bison again, with Lee and Bettencourt connecting from 3-point range, and McNaughton powering his way inside for easy baskets. Trying for its fourth NCAA tournament berth this decade, Holy Cross (20-12) instead came up short to the Bison in the title game for the second straight season. Kevin Hamilton scored 20 points and Keith Simmons added 19 for the Crusaders, who hope to get an NIT bid for the second season in a row. With a frenzied, orange-clad crowd rocking the Sojka Pavilion, McNaughton slipped behind the defense for a couple of baskets early in the second half that stretched what had been a tight game to a nine-point lead for Bucknell. Then the Bison really got rolling. Bettencourt hit a 3, and reserve Donald Brown scored five straight points on a dunk and a three-point play that made it 57-44. Lee finished with 16 points and was named tournament MVP. Brown and McNaughton each had 14. The Crusaders got sloppy, started turning the ball over and couldn't hit a shot. They went scoreless for a 6:09 stretch midway through the second half that allowed the Bison to keep a double-digit lead. Bettencourt delivered the decisive blow late in the game when he was fouled on a 3-pointer from the right side and sank the free throw for a 15-point lead. Bettencourt added a fast-break layup that made it 72-57 with about 1:30 left and the crowd started chanting "Undefeated!" "He's always dangerous because if you give him an opportunity to shoot the basketball, he's going to knock it down," said Holy Cross coach Ralph Willard. "It doesn't take much time for him to get them off. He's a senior and he's going to make big plays." Bettencourt went 6-for-10 from 3-point range, Lee was 3-for-5 and the Bison made 10 of 18 overall on 3s. Holy Cross committed 19 turnovers that led to 20 Bucknell points. Yes, that "Round of 32" banner proudly displayed on the gym's wall won't have anyone placing Bucknell with the Duke's and North Carolina's among college basketball's royalty, but not many teams from mid-major conferences have received as much national attention the last two seasons. Bucknell got their first, albeit short-lived, national ranking this season, and beat No. 17 Syracuse in November. They've played on national television, set a home attendance record earlier this season against Villanova, and knew every opponent was looking to take a piece out of the Giant Killers. "We've gotten people's best punch all year and I think we got Holy Cross' again today, but I think we did a great job of handling it," Lee said. Now they wait to find out where and who they'll play in the tournament. The Bison weren't worried about that quite yet, not with two nights of celebration ahead. "We'll enjoy it, go out to eat, get some soda pop and get ready for the tournament," Lee said.
